{"term":"1964","caseName":"Dixon v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1964/486","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 31, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14357","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"W. Palmer Dixon, et al., Petitioner versus United States.","start":0,"stop":6.308,"duration":6.31},{"text":"Mr. Goodman, you may continue your argument.","start":6.308,"stop":8.736,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":8.736,"stop":11.884,"duration":3.15},{"text":"When we broke off yesterday, I had just offered an analogy which in our view aptly illustrates the basic principle of this case.","start":11.884,"stop":20.699,"duration":8.82},{"text":"I suggested that if A lends B $100 today, in return for B's promise to repay the $100 plus $6 extra one year from today, B's obligation could be expressed in the note in a number of different ways, all of which mean exactly the same thing.","start":20.699,"stop":41.112,"duration":20.41},{"text":"The note could say $100 plus 6% interest or $100 plus 6% or $100 plus $6 or as in the present case, the note could simply say $106.","start":41.112,"stop":55.072,"duration":13.96},{"text":"In each of these cases, the $6 increment simply represents the compensation which the borrower agrees to pay the lender in return for the lender's money, in short, interest as this Court has defined it.","start":55.072,"stop":69.382,"duration":14.31},{"text":"Everyone agrees that in the case of the note with 6% stated interest an accrual basis taxpayer would be required to accrue the $6 increment over the life of the note and we say exactly the same result should obtain in the case of $106 note issued at a $6 discount.","start":69.382,"stop":89.019,"duration":19.64},{"text":"A cash basis taxpayer of course would not be required to account for the gain until he sold or redeemed the note.","start":89.019,"stop":96.572,"duration":7.55},{"text":"At that time, he would be deemed to be selling two things; first, the note itself carrying with it the right to interest accruing in the future, and secondly, the right to the interest that had already been earned up to the date of the sale or redemption.","start":96.572,"stop":112.401,"duration":15.83},{"text":"Part of the purchase price would have to be allocated to the note and the rest of it would have to be allocated to the interest component and that part allocated to the interest component would be taxable as ordinary income.","start":112.401,"stop":125.512,"duration":13.11}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What if the going rate of interest changed between the time of the issuance of the note and the sale of third party and which would affect the price because of the going of the change and the going rate of interest.","start":125.512,"stop":140.259,"duration":14.75}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":140.259,"stop":140.515,"duration":0.26},{"text":"Well, if -- let's suppose first that nothing happens and he sells the note at the end of six months for $103.","start":140.515,"stop":146.777,"duration":6.26}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the case you've already given.","start":146.777,"stop":147.97,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":147.97,"stop":148.302,"duration":0.33},{"text":"In that case, there would be no capital gain or loss and there would be interest income of $3.","start":148.302,"stop":152.963,"duration":4.66},{"text":"If the market rate of interest increased we'll say, so that he was able to sell the note only for $102, the result in that case roughly speaking, not quite exactly, but roughly speaking, would be a $1 capital loss and $3 of interest income.","start":152.963,"stop":171.528,"duration":18.56},{"text":"It wouldn't be exactly that because the $102 would have to be -- well 100, one hundred and thirds of that would have to be allocated to the note and three one hundred and thirds to the interest element and would come out that he had perhaps received about $2.97 of interest and slightly less than $100 would be attributable to the note in that case.","start":171.528,"stop":195.406,"duration":23.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that a good deal of this problem has been explicitly covered in the 1954 --","start":195.406,"stop":200.82,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":200.82,"stop":203.001,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I right in my understanding that with respect to the note of an individual person --","start":203.001,"stop":209.724,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":209.724,"stop":210.02,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The 54 statute does not --","start":210.02,"stop":211.314,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, the 54 statute applies only to securities issued by a corporation or by a governmental entity.","start":211.314,"stop":218.839,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you explain to us why that happened Mr. Goodman, why the individual was left out?","start":218.839,"stop":224.045,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I think for the most part Mr. Justice Goldberg, the 1954 statute was intended primarily as a legislative overruling of the Caulkins case.","start":224.045,"stop":233.431,"duration":9.39},{"text":"They primarily were thinking within the general framework of that decision and simply didn't provide a legislative solution which went to the heart of the principle.","start":233.431,"stop":244.877,"duration":11.45}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Had the Treasury proposed a broader solution, do you know?","start":244.877,"stop":248.869,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so.","start":248.869,"stop":249.998,"duration":1.13},{"text":"I maybe wrong about that.","start":249.998,"stop":251.046,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I don't think they did.","start":251.046,"stop":255.373,"duration":4.33},{"text":"The taxpayer concedes all of this in the case of the note with stated interest and we say that exactly the same principle should apply in the case of the discounted note.","start":255.373,"stop":265.063,"duration":9.69},{"text":"This conclusion is compelled not only by reason, it is supported also by the overwhelming weight of authority.","start":265.063,"stop":271.853,"duration":6.79},{"text":"Since 1959, the basic issue involved in this case has come before six Courts of Appeals, the Court of Claims and the Tax Court.","start":271.853,"stop":280.362,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Only one court, the Sixth Circuit in the Midland-Ross case has resolved the matter in favor of the taxpayer.","start":280.362,"stop":287.5,"duration":7.14},{"text":"All of the others, the First, Second, Third, Fifth and Ninth Circuits have recognized that original issue discount is exactly the same thing as interest and should be taxed as such.","start":287.5,"stop":299.769,"duration":12.27},{"text":"The conclusion is further supported by the long-standing rule as to the treatment of original issue discount from the standpoint of the borrower, that is to say, the corporation which issues the security.","start":299.769,"stop":310.508,"duration":10.74},{"text":"The decisions of this and other courts have uniformly held that this -- that the excess of the amount which the borrower agrees to pay upon maturity over the amount at which the security is issued, represents a cost of obtaining the lender's money and as such must be amortized over the life of the note and deductible from ordinary income.","start":310.508,"stop":333.507,"duration":23},{"text":"It is true that at least one Court of Appeals, the Second Circuit has thought it more appropriate to regard this deductible item as a cost sustained by the issuing corporation rather than its interest.","start":333.507,"stop":346.102,"duration":12.59},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit has regarded it alternatively, either as interest or as a cost.","start":346.102,"stop":352.07,"duration":5.97},{"text":"But three other Courts of Appeals, the Third, the Fourth and the D.C. Circuit have concluded unequivocally that original issue discount is deductible as an interest expense by the issuing corporation.","start":352.07,"stop":364.817,"duration":12.75},{"text":"At page 15 of our brief in the Midland-Ross case, we cite the well-reasoned opinions of Judge Goodrich for the Third Circuit and Judge Parker for the Fourth Circuit.","start":364.817,"stop":375.798,"duration":10.98},{"text":"We neglected to cite the third case which is Helvering versus California-Oregon Power Company, 75 F.2d 64, the decision of the District of Columbia Circuit.","start":375.798,"stop":388.066,"duration":12.27},{"text":"The same --","start":388.066,"stop":388.773,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":388.773,"stop":392.462,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Of this aspect?","start":392.462,"stop":393.517,"duration":1.06},{"text":"We regard it as an interest deduction.","start":393.517,"stop":395.487,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Both sides?","start":395.487,"stop":396.803,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"On both sides -- as an interest deduction by the issuer and as an interest income to the lender.","start":396.803,"stop":403.199,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":403.199,"stop":412.327,"duration":9.13}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not quite sure, I understand what that means Mr. Justice Goldberg.","start":412.327,"stop":415.398,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":415.398,"stop":421.057,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"You're distinguishing the yield from the nominal rate of interest.","start":421.057,"stop":423.341,"duration":2.28},{"text":"I believe that's true.","start":423.341,"stop":424.179,"duration":0.84},{"text":"I've read that Mr. Justice Goldberg.","start":424.179,"stop":427.036,"duration":2.86},{"text":"In regard to the question that you just asked, in view of the contention by Midland-Ross that the government has taken a different view with regard to the status of original issue of discount to the borrower, Midland-Ross says that the government regards this as a loss rather than as interest.","start":427.036,"stop":447.142,"duration":20.11},{"text":"It's true that the government has been inconsistent about this over the course of the years and at times has regarded it as a loss.","start":447.142,"stop":453.081,"duration":5.94},{"text":"But so far as I know, the most recent expression is contained in the ruling which we quote on page 36 of the Midland-Ross brief which says -- states as follows, the final paragraph from the footnote.","start":453.081,"stop":468.208,"duration":15.13},{"text":"The courts have considered the nature of discount in cases involving private corporations and have held it to be in the nature of differed interest which maybe amortized for income tax purposes over the life of the bonds by deducting the annual proportion thereof from the issuing corporations' gross income each year as accrued interest.","start":468.208,"stop":490.674,"duration":22.47},{"text":"The leading decision of -- oh, I was going to present one further citation which we didn't give in our brief, and that is to the Longview Hilton Hotel Company case, 9 T.C. 180, 182 and the case is cited therein, which I think expresses the view of most of the cases of the Tax Court to the effect that it is an interest deduction to the borrower.","start":490.674,"stop":514.804,"duration":24.13},{"text":"The leading decision of this Court, Helvering versus Union Pacific Company is a little bit ambivalent.","start":514.804,"stop":520.773,"duration":5.97},{"text":"At some point, the Court appears to refer to the original issue of discount item as a loss.","start":520.773,"stop":529.382,"duration":8.61},{"text":"But it also states that discount is a factor “in arriving at the actual amount of interest paid for the use of capital procured by a bond issue.”","start":529.382,"stop":538.977,"duration":9.6},{"text":"The difference between the capital realized by the issuer and par value which is to be paid at maturity, must be added to the aggregate coupon payments in order to arrive at the total interest paid.","start":538.977,"stop":550.739,"duration":11.76},{"text":"Now if as these authorities seem to indicate, original issue discount represents interest paid or accrued by the borrower, then necessarily it represents income, it represents interest received or accrued by the lender.","start":550.739,"stop":565.87,"duration":15.13},{"text":"Petitioners don't really dispute the fact that original issue discount and stated interest are in substance one and the same thing.","start":565.87,"stop":573.147,"duration":7.28},{"text":"They argue however, that the government is estopped to deny them capital gains treatment because of its earlier acquiescence in the Sixth Circuit's decision in the Caulkins case.","start":573.147,"stop":583.11,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you get to that, how do you handle the consistent treatment of premium or have you told us about it?","start":583.11,"stop":591.019,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice Stewart, I agree with the petitioners that premium logically should be treated the same way as discount and vice versa and also that prior to 1942, I think it was the general understanding that premium was not to be regarded as an item which ended into the computation of interest but rather as a capital item to use that terminology.","start":591.019,"stop":615.704,"duration":24.68},{"text":"However, the two questions have historically been treated as separate compartments, altogether apart from one another at least much of the time.","start":615.704,"stop":622.842,"duration":7.14},{"text":"In 1942, Congress enacted a statute dealing expressly with the problem of bond premium and said not a word about bond discount.","start":622.842,"stop":631.777,"duration":8.94},{"text":"In 1954, it enacted a statute dealing with original issue discount and said not a word about premium and in some respects, the two statutory solutions are not parallel.","start":631.777,"stop":641.603,"duration":9.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible] dealing with discount to what the law was before.","start":641.603,"stop":647.521,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"The House Committee as Mr. Brandes said yesterday stated that the prior law was that the discount was a capital item and was not interest.","start":647.521,"stop":656.992,"duration":9.47},{"text":"On the other hand --","start":656.992,"stop":657.356,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now your view of -- your position is that's just plain wrong.","start":657.356,"stop":661.164,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That was -- we think that was an erroneous and overly broad statement.","start":661.164,"stop":666.607,"duration":5.44},{"text":"The Senate on the -- the Senate Committee on the other hand, took a different view.","start":666.607,"stop":669.579,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It said that the law simply was not clear and that the purpose of the House Bill, the 1944 legislation having originated in the House was simply to clarify the preexisting law and to remove all uncertainties and doubts.","start":669.579,"stop":683.693,"duration":14.11},{"text":"So at least as far as the Senate is concerned, I don't think there is any negative implication in the 1954 legislation.","start":683.693,"stop":689.517,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the 1954 legislation would have applied to the one who loans on a note and a discount and what if he sells the note then, meanwhile?","start":689.517,"stop":708.814,"duration":19.3},{"text":"If he sells the note meanwhile then that fellow gets paid off with it.","start":708.814,"stop":713.127,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":713.127,"stop":713.615,"duration":0.49},{"text":"I think that --","start":713.615,"stop":714.037,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Both of them have interest.","start":714.037,"stop":716.14,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the 19 -- if the first -- if the original holder of the note sells it, he is chargeable with that part of the discount interest which it accrued up to the date of the sale.","start":716.14,"stop":727.804,"duration":11.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the buyer?","start":727.804,"stop":729.371,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Is accountable for the balance of the interest as it accrues during his holding period.","start":729.371,"stop":735.288,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the discount where -- this is only -- this applies only where there is a interest not stated?","start":735.288,"stop":753.832,"duration":18.54}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":753.832,"stop":754.244,"duration":0.41},{"text":"The statute applies to original issue discount.","start":754.244,"stop":756.947,"duration":2.7},{"text":"That result would have been true with -- I think everyone agrees that, that result would have been -- would have obtained in the cases where interest was stated.","start":756.947,"stop":764.862,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But that -- you said yesterday that was only as of 1954, there was a case on that.","start":764.862,"stop":770.41,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":770.41,"stop":770.859,"duration":0.45},{"text":"What I said yesterday was this.","start":770.859,"stop":773.027,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Well, the question you ask I believe is what treatment would have been accorded to the sale of a security with accrued interest where the purchase price was not specifically allocated between the two components.","start":773.027,"stop":789.113,"duration":16.09},{"text":"And my answer was that the earliest case on this so far as I know is the Fischer case decided in 1954.","start":789.113,"stop":796.893,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Since then, there had been a number of cases which have confirmed the result that you must allocate the purchase price between the interest and principal component.","start":796.893,"stop":806.744,"duration":9.85},{"text":"Prior to that time, there was no specific case and I think that the matter was inconsiderable, valid and confusion.","start":806.744,"stop":813.323,"duration":6.58},{"text":"That was not the result of any statutory change in 1954.","start":813.323,"stop":822.26,"duration":8.94},{"text":"I was answering Mr. Justice Stewart's question about premium.","start":822.26,"stop":827.978,"duration":5.72},{"text":"Not only has Congress treated premium and discount differently, but this Court has also tended to regard them as separate questions.","start":827.978,"stop":836.18,"duration":8.2},{"text":"In 1932, a much criticized decision, the Old Colony case, this Court held in effect that premium was not to be taken into account in computing the interest deductions for the issuer.","start":836.18,"stop":852.427,"duration":16.25},{"text":"The Court said that interest meant what everybody -- interest meant what is called interest.","start":852.427,"stop":857.828,"duration":5.4},{"text":"It meant the nominal interest rate and it didn't have anything to do with what the Court called the esoteric notion of effective interest dreamed up by accountants.","start":857.828,"stop":866.81,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Two years later though in 1936 in the Union Pacific case to which I've already referred, the Court said that original issue discount as distinct from premium was to be taken into account in determining the issuer's interest deductions so that it treated premium and interest differently -- premium and discount differently.","start":866.81,"stop":886.957,"duration":20.15},{"text":"And as I've already indicated, the lower federal courts have fairly consistently though not entirely consistently treated discount as an interest item to the borrower without so much as nod to the Old Colony case and its ruling as to premium.","start":886.957,"stop":904.985,"duration":18.03},{"text":"This disparity of treatment was noted by no less than observer than Roswell Magill who stated at page 184, I think it was.","start":904.985,"stop":913.797,"duration":8.81},{"text":"I have that somewhere, stated at page 184 of his well known book on tax -- 204 rather, of his well known book on taxable income that the Union Pacific decision with regard to discount is “hardly reconcilable on theories of accrual accounting with the prior holding as to bond premium.”","start":913.797,"stop":937.893,"duration":24.1},{"text":"So while I don't pretend to defend a differentiation in treatment between premium and discount.","start":937.893,"stop":945.541,"duration":7.65},{"text":"I don't think that the Court need deter from reaching the sound and sensible result in the case of discount merely because of early and long since discredited decisions about premium which in any event were superseded by statute as early as 1942, long before the transactions in this case.","start":945.541,"stop":962.378,"duration":16.84}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Your answer -- your explanation does indicate that plenty of -- there are plenty of examples and you've given us, one where things which are a matter of economics are alive have because of the labels attributed to -- has been treated differently by this Court and other courts.","start":962.378,"stop":980.602,"duration":18.22},{"text":"You've just told us about premium and discount and the same might well be true about discount and the interest even though economically, these things are all in a parity, still the labels that people have given to them have rightly or wrongly influenced the courts to different results and again --","start":980.602,"stop":996.127,"duration":15.52}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't -- I don't --","start":996.127,"stop":997.012,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Results which is a matter of economics or interest.","start":997.012,"stop":999.116,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think I can deny that Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":999.116,"stop":1001.716,"duration":2.6},{"text":"I would emphasize your word wrongly though, in the case of Old Colony decision which all of the accounting commentators have roundly criticized even while it still had a lot of vitality and I don't think it has much anymore.","start":1001.716,"stop":1014.42,"duration":12.7},{"text":"Now turning to the Caulkins' decision and the contention that the government is estopped by virtue of its acquiescence in that case, we think that, that contention fails for two reasons.","start":1014.42,"stop":1024.558,"duration":10.14},{"text":"The first place, because the government is not bound by its acquiescence and in the second place, because in any event, the Caulkins' decision does not rule this case.","start":1024.558,"stop":1033.568,"duration":9.01},{"text":"It's well settled I think that acquiescence in an erroneous decision does not preclude the government from correcting its mistake and collecting a tax otherwise due.","start":1033.568,"stop":1043.96,"duration":10.39},{"text":"The taxpayer cannot claim surprise in this regard because the cumulative bulletin, every cumulative bulletin says on its very front page that the rulings contain therein and that includes acquiescence are not binding but are simply intended as guides to official administrative prudent, administrative thinking.","start":1043.96,"stop":1063.48,"duration":19.52},{"text":"The statute expressly gives the Commissioner discretion to determine the extent to which any ruling maybe applied without retroactive effect.","start":1063.48,"stop":1072.89,"duration":9.41},{"text":"The taxpayer says that in this case, that abuse -- that discretion was abused because the Commissioner made the withdrawal of his acquiescence retroactive with respect to all taxpayers other than those who had purchase the particular type of security involved in the Caulkins case.","start":1072.89,"stop":1088.962,"duration":16.07},{"text":"Now we don't say that the differentiation between that type of security and other types of securities was altogether a reasonable one, but on the other hand, it certainly wasn't arbitrary and invidious.","start":1088.962,"stop":1100.272,"duration":11.31},{"text":"The government simply made a limited vow in the direction of stare decisis much as this Court did when it held that football and boxing were subject to the antitrust laws but refrained from extending that principle to baseball which was the particular sport which had been covered by the prior decision in Tulsan exempting it from the antitrust laws.","start":1100.272,"stop":1124.726,"duration":24.45},{"text":"In any event, the Caulkins case really isn't in point here.","start":1124.726,"stop":1128.592,"duration":3.87},{"text":"The Caulkins arose under a particular statute, Section 117F of the 1939 code which dealt only with the retirement of bonds and the decision was very much based upon the particular language of that statute.","start":1128.592,"stop":1142.773,"duration":14.18},{"text":"In Caulkins, the taxpayer purchased for about $15,000 payable in ten annual installments, an installment certificate in the face amount of $20,000 which he surrendered for that amount.","start":1142.773,"stop":1154.833,"duration":12.06},{"text":"That represented the equivalent of a 5.5% return on his investment.","start":1154.833,"stop":1159.176,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And indeed, the 5.5% was even written on the cover of the certificate.","start":1159.176,"stop":1164.262,"duration":5.09},{"text":"The Court held that this was capital gain under the language of Section 117F which provided that amounts received upon the retirement of corporate bonds would be considered to be received in exchange therefore.","start":1164.262,"stop":1177.333,"duration":13.07},{"text":"The Court didn't base its decision upon any broad, general principle that original issue discount was different from interest or had traditionally been treated differently.","start":1177.333,"stop":1186.432,"duration":9.1},{"text":"In fact, specifically agreed with the government, that the discount was essentially the same as interest and that there was no practical reason for taxing it other than as ordinary income, but it felt compelled by the particular language of Section 117F to hold it capital gain.","start":1186.432,"stop":1202.883,"duration":16.45},{"text":"I think it's quite probable that the Court would have reached the same result in the case of a note with stated interest and it might well have reached a different result had the discounts been realized upon a transaction not covered by Section 117F, in other words, by a sale.","start":1202.883,"stop":1221.816,"duration":18.93},{"text":"Now this interpretation of the Caulkins' decision is by no means a novel one.","start":1221.816,"stop":1226.439,"duration":4.62},{"text":"Even before the government withdrew its acquiescence in Caulkins, the Tax Court held that the rule of Caulkins was confined to retirements and did not apply to sale and I'd like to read the Court exactly what the Tax Court said in that regard.","start":1226.439,"stop":1243.108,"duration":16.67},{"text":"It said in the Paine case 23 T.C. 391 and 401, we think it clear that the decision in the Caulkins case was based solely upon the precise language of Section 117F which left no doubt that the entire amount received as a result of the retirement of notes and registered form was to be deemed received in exchange for such notes despite the recognition of both courts, both the Tax Court and the Court of -- and the Sixth Circuit that the increment there under consideration was essentially interest.","start":1243.108,"stop":1271.774,"duration":28.67},{"text":"It is obvious however that Section 117F is not here applicable because there was no retirement of the notes but only a sale and there is no evidence that the notes were in registered form.","start":1271.774,"stop":1283.143,"duration":11.37}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The Paine case was reversed by the Court of Appeals?","start":1283.143,"stop":1285.141,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"It was reversed on grounds which are completely irrelevant to this consideration.","start":1285.141,"stop":1290.637,"duration":5.5},{"text":"It was reversed essentially on the ground that in that case, the notes in question had been given in return for property.","start":1290.637,"stop":1299.332,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So it didn't get to this ground --","start":1299.332,"stop":1301.227,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1301.227,"stop":1301.941,"duration":0.71},{"text":"They concluded that there was no interest element at all in the case because they didn't know what the value of the property was.","start":1301.941,"stop":1306.813,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1306.813,"stop":1323.582,"duration":16.77}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Premium is governed by a different statute which was enacted in 1942.","start":1323.582,"stop":1328.6,"duration":5.02},{"text":"In general, the treatment is similar.","start":1328.6,"stop":1330.361,"duration":1.76},{"text":"The treatment --","start":1330.361,"stop":1330.856,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1330.856,"stop":1332.633,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well yes, I suppose it was.","start":1332.633,"stop":1334.134,"duration":1.5},{"text":"The difference in treatment --","start":1334.134,"stop":1335.241,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1335.241,"stop":1340.349,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they're very similar.","start":1340.349,"stop":1341.444,"duration":1.1},{"text":"I don't mean to suggest that they're entirely different.","start":1341.444,"stop":1343.211,"duration":1.77},{"text":"On the contrary, they're almost the same, but only almost the same.","start":1343.211,"stop":1346.83,"duration":3.62},{"text":"For example, the statute dealing with premium deals with both market premium and original issue premium, the distinction I haven't --","start":1346.83,"stop":1355.607,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1355.607,"stop":1359.849,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the statute provides that it -- the statute gives the lender an election to either to amortize it over the life of -- amortize it as a deduction over the life of the security or to treat it as a loss in the year of sale or redemption, it has that choice.","start":1359.849,"stop":1380.552,"duration":20.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1380.552,"stop":1381.969,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute doesn't deal with the element that pays it.","start":1381.969,"stop":1384.023,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1384.023,"stop":1389.277,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he is required to amortize it.","start":1389.277,"stop":1397.554,"duration":8.28},{"text":"Now as I indicated earlier, the Old Colony case said that you don't amortize it as an interest deduction but it left open the possibility at least after 1913 of amortizing it as income received by the issuer.","start":1397.554,"stop":1417.167,"duration":19.61},{"text":"So that really, it is treated in exactly the same way as we argue that discount should be treated, but I have to concede that it was not on the theory that it was an interest deduction.","start":1417.167,"stop":1427.417,"duration":10.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1427.417,"stop":1433.345,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd like to correct what I just said.","start":1433.345,"stop":1435.096,"duration":1.75},{"text":"I was a little bit confused.","start":1435.096,"stop":1436.344,"duration":1.25},{"text":"He is allowed to amortize it but not on the theory that it is an offset to interest.","start":1436.344,"stop":1443.294,"duration":6.95},{"text":"In other words, if a bond is purchased for 100 -- for $94 and it's a $100 bond --","start":1443.294,"stop":1451.169,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1451.169,"stop":1452.721,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, alright if it's purchased for $100 and it has a face amount say of $94, it's purchased at a premium.","start":1452.721,"stop":1458.715,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The $6 premium that is received by the issuer is required to be amortized as income by the issuer over the term of the security.","start":1458.715,"stop":1471.721,"duration":13.01},{"text":"Now originally in the Old Colony case, the government argued that this should be true because you should treat the $6 as a factor which enters into the computation of his interest deduction in subsequent years.","start":1471.721,"stop":1483.678,"duration":11.96},{"text":"You should treat it as an offset to his interest deduction in subsequent years as reducing his interest deduction.","start":1483.678,"stop":1490.044,"duration":6.37},{"text":"The Court held in Old Colony, no that wasn't the proper way of looking at interest, but it did leave the way open for amortizing it nonetheless and this would have the same effect.","start":1490.044,"stop":1500.904,"duration":10.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1500.904,"stop":1507.313,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"He is the lender.","start":1507.313,"stop":1508.434,"duration":1.12},{"text":"He is the person who was governed by the statute and he is permitted -- he is given an election as to whether to amortize it or as to whether to treat it as a loss in the year in which he sells the bond or redeems it.","start":1508.434,"stop":1520.587,"duration":12.15},{"text":"That was the statutory solution adopted in 1942.","start":1520.587,"stop":1524.096,"duration":3.51},{"text":"Now I suppose that in most cases he would be -- he would choose to amortize it and treat it as an ordinary loss so that the election aspect of the statute --","start":1524.096,"stop":1536.394,"duration":12.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1536.394,"stop":1542.594,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1542.594,"stop":1543.361,"duration":0.77},{"text":"From the lender's side, it is a deductible item.","start":1543.361,"stop":1546.34,"duration":2.98},{"text":"It increases his interest if you want to look at it that way.","start":1546.34,"stop":1550.219,"duration":3.88},{"text":"The statute doesn't say anything about interest.","start":1550.219,"stop":1552.018,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1552.018,"stop":1556.14,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"It increases his interest deduction.","start":1556.14,"stop":1557.937,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1557.937,"stop":1560.027,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1560.027,"stop":1560.574,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1560.574,"stop":1584.243,"duration":23.67}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, he is -- excuse me.","start":1584.243,"stop":1586.808,"duration":2.57},{"text":"I've been confusing you I'm afraid.","start":1586.808,"stop":1590.004,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Excuse me, he is the person who is receiving the interest.","start":1590.004,"stop":1593.614,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The lender received --","start":1593.614,"stop":1594.618,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1594.618,"stop":1594.974,"duration":0.36},{"text":"He is the recipient.","start":1594.974,"stop":1596.014,"duration":1.04},{"text":"The lender is the recipient of interest.","start":1596.014,"stop":1597.793,"duration":1.78},{"text":"He has no interest deduction.","start":1597.793,"stop":1599.393,"duration":1.6},{"text":"The lender may treat this $6 premium which he has had to pay at the time he purchases the bond as a deduction amortized over the life of the asset.","start":1599.393,"stop":1609.074,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But it offsets the interest that he receives.","start":1609.074,"stop":1611.18,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1611.18,"stop":1611.772,"duration":0.59},{"text":"It offsets the interest which he received.","start":1611.772,"stop":1613.82,"duration":2.05},{"text":"Now the statute doesn't say that that's the theory of the deduction.","start":1613.82,"stop":1617.7,"duration":3.88},{"text":"It simply says that he may deduct it.","start":1617.7,"stop":1619.483,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Now it's not clear whether he may deduct it as a loss or as an offset to the interest which he received.","start":1619.483,"stop":1624.183,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now that -- now is that statutory?","start":1624.183,"stop":1627.675,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is statutory in the case of the lender, yes.","start":1627.675,"stop":1631.527,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And did that change the rule of the cases?","start":1631.527,"stop":1634.917,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1634.917,"stop":1636.117,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The cases were treated as a capital.","start":1636.117,"stop":1638.358,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, it treated -- it changed the rule of the New York Life Insurance Company case which --","start":1638.358,"stop":1643.513,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as the lender is concerned by statute now, discount and premium were treated almost --","start":1643.513,"stop":1651.906,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Almost the same, that's correct Mr. Justice White.","start":1651.906,"stop":1654.375,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Inaudible]","start":1654.375,"stop":1668.667,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Goodman yesterday afternoon in his statement of the facts, inadvertently but yet very peculiarly significant reason, I am afraid misdescribed the facts.","start":1668.667,"stop":1684.959,"duration":16.29},{"text":"Mr. Goodman's mistake was that he stated that in the transactions here involved, I beg your pardon, it was an economic loss of consequence.","start":1684.959,"stop":1696.097,"duration":11.14},{"text":"The fact is however that there was an economic gain of substance.","start":1696.097,"stop":1702.607,"duration":6.51},{"text":"This was examined by the Treasury Department on audit and they were satisfied.","start":1702.607,"stop":1708.405,"duration":5.8},{"text":"And that is why the question of whether or not there was an economic gain in this transaction was not raised in either in the lower courts or raised until yesterday -- or stated until yesterday afternoon.","start":1708.405,"stop":1722.783,"duration":14.38},{"text":"Now the reason why Mr. Goodman made that mistake is that he compared the gain on the sales of the securities made in 1952 with the interest course of carrying the entire position including those securities which were first sold in 1953.","start":1722.783,"stop":1743.436,"duration":20.65},{"text":"The significance of the mistake is that it emphasizes the difference between an investment including a discount obligation and stated interest.","start":1743.436,"stop":1754.663,"duration":11.23},{"text":"You don't know the results on an investment until the investment is fully disposed of.","start":1754.663,"stop":1762.233,"duration":7.57},{"text":"It is only then that the economic consequences are in hand.","start":1762.233,"stop":1768.804,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you do know what the consequences would be if you hold it for the good.","start":1768.804,"stop":1772.766,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"If all things work out as you hope they will.","start":1772.766,"stop":1775.996,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean -- all you mean is that the lender can pay?","start":1775.996,"stop":1779.234,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"If the lender can pay.","start":1779.234,"stop":1780.301,"duration":1.07},{"text":"If the lender remains --","start":1780.301,"stop":1781.533,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Or if the borrower can pay you back, now you -- that's the risk.","start":1781.533,"stop":1785.421,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, the lender -- that the borrower remains solvent and able to meet his obligation.","start":1785.421,"stop":1793.343,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Now, strangely and interestingly --","start":1793.343,"stop":1796.535,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know why the -- does the record show why these notes were sold?","start":1796.535,"stop":1806.516,"duration":9.98}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is not in the record.","start":1806.516,"stop":1807.863,"duration":1.35},{"text":"It is conceded that they were sold and in bona fide sales.","start":1807.863,"stop":1812.388,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but [Inaudible]","start":1812.388,"stop":1821.188,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"A period of time that probably differed as between various obligations maybe somewhat so closer to maturity and others were so -- at a period of time further removed from the maturity.","start":1821.188,"stop":1835.403,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You would have held that no maturity --","start":1835.403,"stop":1837.264,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"If they had been held to maturity under the statute as it existed prior of 1954, the gain would have been ordinary income because these obligations were not in registered form or with coupons attached and the significance given in the statute on a retirement was limited to obligations in registered form or with coupons attached.","start":1837.264,"stop":1862.558,"duration":25.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well is this pretty solvent borrower?","start":1862.558,"stop":1865.896,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The borrowers were solvent.","start":1865.896,"stop":1867.982,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And that this must [Inaudible]","start":1867.982,"stop":1871.449,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"They were sold and there is no -- as I mentioned, no argument made about the sale.","start":1871.449,"stop":1878.276,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I understand you to say that, had they been held to maturity, then it would have been treated as an income and not as --","start":1878.276,"stop":1885.604,"duration":7.33}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The gain would not have been a capital gain because the threshold item of a sale or exchange would be missing.","start":1885.604,"stop":1895.643,"duration":10.04},{"text":"117F which makes a retirement, a deemed exchange was then limited to obligations and registered form or with coupons attached.","start":1895.643,"stop":1906.721,"duration":11.08},{"text":"That requirement was eliminated in the 1954 code.","start":1906.721,"stop":1912.155,"duration":5.43},{"text":"Now, I wanted at this point to bring in the analogy of the premium case, the leading case on premium in this Court, the New York Life Insurance against Edwards.","start":1912.155,"stop":1925.052,"duration":12.9},{"text":"There the Court pointed out that only on disposition could it be known whether or not a security issued at a premium would produce profit or loss and that is why the lender was not to be permitted to amortize his premium course as against his income currently and I should like to take the liberty of reading the words of the Court.","start":1925.052,"stop":1951.152,"duration":26.1},{"text":"Obviously, no actual ascertainable loss had occurred.","start":1951.152,"stop":1955.996,"duration":4.84},{"text":"All of the securities might have been sold thereafter above cost.","start":1955.996,"stop":1960.39,"duration":4.39},{"text":"The result of the venture could not be known until they were either sold or paid off.","start":1960.39,"stop":1972.128,"duration":11.74},{"text":"Mr. Justice Goldberg raised the question of whether the new provision in the 1954 code applies to obligations of an individual.","start":1972.128,"stop":1982.258,"duration":10.13},{"text":"For some reason, Congress has not done that but by the same token, the privilege of amortizing premium is not allowed with regard to obligations issued by individuals.","start":1982.258,"stop":1995,"duration":12.74},{"text":"The two things march along together for reasons apparently best known to the Congress.","start":1995,"stop":2001.279,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now could you tell me now -- could you tell me what -- how premium is now treated under the statute from the standpoint of --","start":2001.279,"stop":2011.139,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Premium on private --","start":2011.139,"stop":2013.344,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"- the lender.","start":2013.344,"stop":2014.526,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Premium paid by the lender on a private security is distinct from a municipal security.","start":2014.526,"stop":2023.786,"duration":9.26},{"text":"He may at the election of the lender be amortized so as to reduce his ordinary income including his income from the obligation which he holds.","start":2023.786,"stop":2035.949,"duration":12.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What's his other election?","start":2035.949,"stop":2039.323,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"His other election is not to make the election which I just described in which event, it is an item of capital gain or loss on disposition of the obligation in the same way as it was before the statute was changed in 1942.","start":2039.323,"stop":2054.367,"duration":15.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now how about public securities?","start":2054.367,"stop":2056.174,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Public securities; the lender is forced to amortize his premium.","start":2056.174,"stop":2062.478,"duration":6.3},{"text":"There is no right of election on public securities, tax exempts and obligation yield on which -- or the income from which, is not subject to federal income tax.","start":2062.478,"stop":2076,"duration":13.52}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What does a borrower do with the same thing, amortize it and set it off against good faith?","start":2076,"stop":2080.382,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2080.382,"stop":2080.748,"duration":0.37},{"text":"He is forced to amortize it but without an offset to income.","start":2080.748,"stop":2086.167,"duration":5.42},{"text":"The -- since the -- the interest on the municipal security is not subject to tax, Congress decided that the premium which was paid should not be permitted to result in an eventual capital loss when the obligation is disposed of.","start":2086.167,"stop":2103.638,"duration":17.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How about the private security?","start":2103.638,"stop":2105.318,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"On the private security, the amortization of the premium is at the election of the lender.","start":2105.318,"stop":2112.081,"duration":6.76},{"text":"He can elect --","start":2112.081,"stop":2113.467,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How about the borrower?","start":2113.467,"stop":2115.025,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The borrower?","start":2115.025,"stop":2116.153,"duration":1.13},{"text":"The borrower must at all times, even at the time when the lender could not reduce his income from the obligation, the borrower must at all times increase as it were his income because he is reducing his cost with regard to the carrying of that obligation.","start":2116.153,"stop":2138.237,"duration":22.08},{"text":"I thank the Court.","start":2138.237,"stop":2141.849,"duration":3.61}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 30, 1965","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14593","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 486, W. Palmer Dixon et al., Petitioners, versus United States.","start":0,"stop":35.295,"duration":35.3},{"text":"Mr. Brandes.","start":35.295,"stop":37.835,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":37.835,"stop":40.228,"duration":2.39},{"text":"This case is before the Court on certiorari to the Second Circuit.","start":40.228,"stop":45.653,"duration":5.42},{"text":"There are two issues involved and the first of the two issues, the same issue is involved in the companion case of the Midland-Ross Corporation in which the government is the petitioner.","start":45.653,"stop":59.335,"duration":13.68},{"text":"That case follows immediately after this case.","start":59.335,"stop":63.904,"duration":4.57},{"text":"So far as the first issue was concerned, the facts are relatively simple.","start":63.904,"stop":70.506,"duration":6.6},{"text":"The year involved is the year 1952 and accordingly the provisions of the 1939 Internal Revenue Code apply.","start":70.506,"stop":80.114,"duration":9.61},{"text":"In that year, the petitioner's here were members of the partnership engaged in the business of dealing in securities.","start":80.114,"stop":89.391,"duration":9.28},{"text":"In addition, the partnership from time to time purchase securities for its own account as principal.","start":89.391,"stop":97.651,"duration":8.26},{"text":"In early nine -- commencing in early 1952, the partnership purchased certain securities consisting of promissory notes that had been issued at a discount and did not bear interest.","start":97.651,"stop":112.957,"duration":15.31},{"text":"It is conceded that these securities were properly identified and marked for investment as is required of a deal of in securities so that they constituted in the hands of the partnership, capital assets.","start":112.957,"stop":130.126,"duration":17.17},{"text":"These securities were sold after -- certain of these notes were sold in 1952 after they have been held for more than six months.","start":130.126,"stop":140.385,"duration":10.26},{"text":"And the gain on the sale was reported by the partnership and therefore by the petitioners as a long-term capital gain.","start":140.385,"stop":149.682,"duration":9.3},{"text":"On audit, the Internal Revenue Service held that the gain which had been reported on sale as long-term capital gain was in reality interest income and so far as the notes which as of the end of the year had not yet been sold, as to those notes even though they had not yet been sold, there was a requirement for a picking up on a pro rata basis of the discount at which those notes had been issued.","start":149.682,"stop":185.312,"duration":35.63},{"text":"The first issue is therefore a very narrow confined issue with statuary construction under the 1939 Code.","start":185.312,"stop":196.883,"duration":11.57},{"text":"It is an issue that does not exist in the context of this case under the 1954 Code because as we propose to develop the law that has been changed.”","start":196.883,"stop":209.925,"duration":13.04},{"text":"Properly stated was, the issue is very simple, what under the 1939 Code was the status of issue discount and to what is the answer to that question is to be determined only in the light of the words of the statute as written, in the light of a demonstrated intent of Congress and in the light of such precedent as we have on the issue and so far as precedent is concerned, the only precedent close to this issue consists of decisions of this Court.","start":209.925,"stop":246.437,"duration":36.51},{"text":"Now, in the court below and continued here, the respondent has offered a very simple, disarming approach to the issue.","start":246.437,"stop":257.827,"duration":11.39},{"text":"The respondent's approach basically is, discount is like compensation for the use of money.","start":257.827,"stop":265.751,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Interest is also compensation for the use of money.","start":265.751,"stop":270.185,"duration":4.43},{"text":"Accordingly, discount and interest must be related and the measure involved of compensation for the use of money must be the measure of ordinary taxable income in the nature of interest that must exist.","start":270.185,"stop":288.567,"duration":18.38},{"text":"Now, this approach which I have taken the liberty of terming it a simple and disarmingly simple approach was fully accepted by the court below and so far as we can ascertain from the opinion, the Court did not proceed to examine what it is that we there offered and there offered again by way of material that shows that Congress was aware, that obligations were issued at a discount and was aware that the tax treatment which attached to obligations that were issued at a discount were different.","start":288.567,"stop":329.966,"duration":41.4},{"text":"Further --","start":329.966,"stop":330.49,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"These were the notes, promissory notes?","start":330.49,"stop":332.2,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":332.2,"stop":333.685,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Purchased from the obligor, from the maker?","start":333.685,"stop":335.502,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"In some instances from the maker and in other instances from other dealers.","start":335.502,"stop":339.767,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"On the date of issue or --","start":339.767,"stop":342.008,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"In all as I remember about one instance on the date of issue.","start":342.008,"stop":345.57,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And in 1952 and then these sales were also within the calendar year 1953?","start":345.57,"stop":349.185,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"These sales were within the calendar year 1952 as to certain of the notes which were thus purchased.","start":349.185,"stop":355.83,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and the only -- that's the only income in question in this case, is it, 1952?","start":355.83,"stop":363.494,"duration":7.66}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in 1952 is the only year before the Court.","start":363.494,"stop":366.8,"duration":3.31},{"text":"However, on audit of 1952, the Internal Revenue Service reclassified the gain on the sale of the notes which were sold.","start":366.8,"stop":375.986,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And in addition, with regard to the unsold notes on the ground that the discount which had been accumulating on those unsold notes, was ordinary income in the nature of interest they forced in accrual.","start":375.986,"stop":390.274,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"These are accruals experience appropriate (Voice Overlap)","start":390.274,"stop":391.631,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"These are accruals -- the partnership is an accrual basis taxpayer.","start":391.631,"stop":395.228,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's not – I probably should know this, but I don't know if the partnership of course is not itself a tax payer.--","start":395.228,"stop":400.878,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right sir.","start":400.878,"stop":401.082,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but a reporter of a return --","start":401.082,"stop":403.246,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The partnership files an --","start":403.246,"stop":404.218,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And if -- if the partnership is on the accrual basis, does this automatically put all the partners on the accrual basis?","start":404.218,"stop":409.079,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":409.079,"stop":409.478,"duration":0.4},{"text":"We thought --","start":409.478,"stop":409.63,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Not such as the business -- as to that part of the income account, a very income account in the partnership or not?","start":409.63,"stop":415.414,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The individuals are not on the accrual basis, but they must pick up in their individual returns, what it is that the partnership return shows as their share of income (Voice Overlap).","start":415.414,"stop":427.284,"duration":11.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though they'd be on a cash basis?","start":427.284,"stop":428.506,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though they'd be on the cash basis.","start":428.506,"stop":430.716,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- what about your --","start":430.716,"stop":432.869,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"The partnership return is just an information --","start":432.869,"stop":435.215,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand -- I know that.","start":435.215,"stop":435.755,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that discloses what it is that each of the partners must report.","start":435.755,"stop":442.963,"duration":7.21},{"text":"Returning to this approach based on compensation for the use of money, although it involves the anticipating part of our argument here, because it is so fundamental to our position to point out and to have the Court realize that the measure of compensation for the use of money is not the measure of interest.","start":442.963,"stop":466.537,"duration":23.57},{"text":"I should like at this point to refer the Court to its decisions in the Bond Premium cases.","start":466.537,"stop":473.752,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Just as that obligation is issued at a discount, it is issued at a premium.","start":473.752,"stop":482.154,"duration":8.4},{"text":"This Court has upheld the treasury in holding that the amount of premium paid does not reduce the amount of interest yield on the obligation, unless there is special legislation.","start":482.154,"stop":498.259,"duration":16.11},{"text":"In other words, if an investor holds an obligation which he acquired at a premium, he is required to pick up and report the full amount of the interest yield without reduction for the premium, unless there is special legislation which authorizes the amortization of the premium, which special legislation came into being in 1942 --","start":498.259,"stop":526.153,"duration":27.89}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And then yield within the technical sense?","start":526.153,"stop":527.623,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me sir.","start":527.623,"stop":528.872,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you using a yield in any technical sense or are you just using it to --","start":528.872,"stop":532.718,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yield in the --","start":532.718,"stop":533.119,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the returns that he had --","start":533.119,"stop":534.153,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the economic --","start":534.153,"stop":534.854,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He must --","start":534.854,"stop":535.242,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or the investments.","start":535.242,"stop":535.595,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"He must return all the interest that you'd paid to him?","start":535.595,"stop":538.534,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right sir, without any reduction.","start":538.534,"stop":541.203,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"It maybe different than yield.","start":541.203,"stop":544.069,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, or -- if you use the terminology of yield, then all the interest that is paid to him is not the yield.","start":544.069,"stop":552.868,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":552.868,"stop":554.357,"duration":1.49},{"text":"That's alright, and then that isn't what you mean.","start":554.357,"stop":557.331,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Do you mean that he has to return all the interest you'd paid to him?","start":557.331,"stop":560.262,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":560.262,"stop":569.737,"duration":9.48},{"text":"Turning to what we believe that we are in a position to prove with regard to the intent of Congress in connection with the 1939 Code as in support of our position that under the 1939 Code, unlike under the 1954 Code, issue discount is a capital item.","start":569.737,"stop":594.002,"duration":24.26},{"text":"We should like to refer to the structure of the statue to the fact that there were specific provisions of the statue which should have been superfluous.","start":594.002,"stop":603.922,"duration":9.92},{"text":"If the rule is as respondent contends namely, if the rule is that issue discount is always an income item.","start":603.922,"stop":615.247,"duration":11.32},{"text":"We also -- to demonstrate the state of the lower pride to the 1954 Code will show that the administrative practice existing at least prior to 1953 was to regard issue discount as a capital item.","start":615.247,"stop":636.378,"duration":21.13},{"text":"The capital gains and losses provisions of the 1939 Code are very clear.","start":636.378,"stop":643.104,"duration":6.73},{"text":"They define capital assets and they further define that any gain realized on the sale of a capital asset is a capital gain and that it is true, is as far as they go and there's -- in that connection.","start":643.104,"stop":661.219,"duration":18.12},{"text":"Within that framework if we went no further, it would be very difficult to find why.","start":661.219,"stop":667.11,"duration":5.89},{"text":"This discount when realized on sale should not be a capital gain.","start":667.11,"stop":672.473,"duration":5.36},{"text":"There was a sale and there was a profit and it was realized after six months.","start":672.473,"stop":679.802,"duration":7.33},{"text":"If we are to believe that there are some hidden, ipso limitations on the definition of what constitutes a capital gain, it is most material to observe that within the framework of Section 117, which is the pertinent Section, the Congress has inserted a very explicit exception.","start":679.802,"stop":704.025,"duration":24.22},{"text":"Securities that have been -- short-term securities that have been issued at a discount and without interest, the statue goes on to say.","start":704.025,"stop":713.788,"duration":9.76},{"text":"By any government, do not constitute capital assets by excluding them from the definition.","start":713.788,"stop":722.118,"duration":8.33},{"text":"Congress saw to it that any gain on those securities was ordinary income.","start":722.118,"stop":728.539,"duration":6.42},{"text":"Now, it is true that the respondent has come forward with some explanation of the background of that section of the statue.","start":728.539,"stop":736.701,"duration":8.16},{"text":"But the fact remains that the existence of this section of the statue shows that the Congress was in a position and knew how to deal with issue discount under the 1939 Code, when it was faced with the need so to deal with issue discount under the 1939 Code.","start":736.701,"stop":756.379,"duration":19.68},{"text":"There were other examples as specific enactments dealing with issue discount that should have been superfluous, if the rule under the 1939 Code was as is contended.","start":756.379,"stop":769.462,"duration":13.08},{"text":"There are special provisions in Section 207(d) and 207(e) dealing with certain insurance companies and specifically requiring those certain insurance companies to accrue and report is ordinary income discount and on the counter balance to accrue and report by way of reduction of ordinary income on premium.","start":769.462,"stop":799.433,"duration":29.97},{"text":"Going back into the legislative history, we find specific statements in the Congress wherein they displayed their understanding and awareness of the fact that debt obligations were issued at a premium under the discount and that different -- were being issued with expressed interest under the discount and that different tax consequences attached to the different types of obligations.","start":799.433,"stop":834.311,"duration":34.88},{"text":"We have at some length delved upon the Senate debate in 1929.","start":834.311,"stop":841.656,"duration":7.34},{"text":"This debate was occasioned by a proposal which authorized the issue of treasury bills at a discount.","start":841.656,"stop":852.357,"duration":10.7},{"text":"At that time, interest on U.S. obligations was exempt from the tax.","start":852.357,"stop":859.158,"duration":6.8},{"text":"It was recognized that to make the treasury bills competitively saleable, there had to be some exemption factor attached to them.","start":859.158,"stop":870.677,"duration":11.52},{"text":"The proposal of the treasury and accepted by the senate finance committee was to attach the exemption factor by providing in the statue that all gain on the sale or rather disposition of these bills should be exempt from tax.","start":870.677,"stop":891.304,"duration":20.63},{"text":"The debate in the Senate shows that there was considerable opposition to such a proposal, because it was felt that there should not be any weakening of the structure which required all capital gains to be subject to tax.","start":891.304,"stop":906.746,"duration":15.44},{"text":"The debate in the senate further shows that the senate was fully aware of the fact that the discount at which these bills were being issued represented to use the words of Senator Reid “Hire for the use of money” and further demonstrates that the Senate believes because it had been so advised by the treasury that under then existing regulations of the treasury, discount, issue discount when realized would be taxed as capital gain.","start":906.746,"stop":938.605,"duration":31.86},{"text":"And accordingly, the exemption for interest which then existed pertaining to obligations of the United States could not apply to a treasury bill.","start":938.605,"stop":951.546,"duration":12.94},{"text":"The Congress again displayed the great awareness of the situation by carving out the discount, by specifically legislating that the discount shall be labeled and classified as interest.","start":951.546,"stop":968.064,"duration":16.52},{"text":"And in that way, the Congress permitted to be attached to the discount at which these bills were issued, the exemption then applying for interest.","start":968.064,"stop":980.234,"duration":12.17},{"text":"In 1938, there was a subcommittee appointed as a part of the study leading to 1939 Code.","start":980.234,"stop":993.302,"duration":13.07},{"text":"This subcommittee considered whether or not to eliminate the capital gains tax.","start":993.302,"stop":1000.293,"duration":6.99},{"text":"Because time is running out, I cannot now read to you the excerpt from this committee's report, but I should like to refer You Honors to it.","start":1000.293,"stop":1010.701,"duration":10.41},{"text":"It is on, page 15 of my brief, and clearly again shows that the Congress was aware of the practice and was aware of the different tax results that existed.","start":1010.701,"stop":1027.236,"duration":16.54},{"text":"I have no place in the respondent's paper been able to find any statement by respondent, that his practice was other than during this period prior to 1953, 1952 and prior, other than to treat issue discount as capital gain.","start":1027.236,"stop":1047.385,"duration":20.15},{"text":"We have in our papers, references to the acquiescence which stood through five major legislative overhauls in a case which held that issue discount when realized was capital gain.","start":1047.385,"stop":1062.25,"duration":14.87},{"text":"At the very beginnings of 1952, there was a special ruling issued in publishing the tax services, which again repeated respondent's position that issue discount when realized was taxable as a capital gain.","start":1062.25,"stop":1078.221,"duration":15.97},{"text":"Now, it's true that the statue was changed in 1954.","start":1078.221,"stop":1084.214,"duration":5.99},{"text":"However, I invite the Court's attention to the structure of the statue.","start":1084.214,"stop":1089.943,"duration":5.73},{"text":"It is as clearly as prospective an application as any statue could be.","start":1089.943,"stop":1099.542,"duration":9.6},{"text":"It applies only to obligations issued after December 31, 1954, and that although the statue itself was passed in August of 1954.","start":1099.542,"stop":1113.075,"duration":13.53},{"text":"Furthermore, in one specific instance, in Section 1232, where they wanted to change the existing rules, they have yet another effective date of March 1954.","start":1113.075,"stop":1129.671,"duration":16.6},{"text":"In connection with the enactment of the 1954 Code, the House Ways and Means Committee clearly stated that this is a change in the law that under the prior law issue discount was taxed when realized as a capital item.","start":1129.671,"stop":1153.096,"duration":23.42},{"text":"With regard -- I have mentioned the situation with regard to bond premium and there legislative history was the same.","start":1153.096,"stop":1160.651,"duration":7.56},{"text":"The situation is to bond premium to bring up more in line with concepts of finance and economics was corrected in 1942.","start":1160.651,"stop":1171.894,"duration":11.24},{"text":"The respondent's answer here apart from the argument to which I have referred is primarily that discount is deductible to the issuer.","start":1171.894,"stop":1183.814,"duration":11.92},{"text":"Now, I can't find that that is an answer to the problem because as regards premium, premium has always been an item of increase to the issuers income even at the time when it was not an item of decrease to the holder's income with regard to the obligation.","start":1183.814,"stop":1211.595,"duration":27.78},{"text":"In summary so far as this first point --","start":1211.595,"stop":1213.729,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Discount is deductible to the issuer?","start":1213.729,"stop":1217.167,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1217.167,"stop":1220.085,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"From his ordinary income whether or not his on the accrual basis?","start":1220.085,"stop":1223.329,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the regulations of the treasury, it must be amortized over the life of the security.","start":1223.329,"stop":1228.806,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What ever his basis is?","start":1228.806,"stop":1229.885,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1229.885,"stop":1230.084,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean whether it'd be cash or accrual?","start":1230.084,"stop":1231.095,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1231.095,"stop":1232.78,"duration":1.68},{"text":"That is correct sir.","start":1232.78,"stop":1238.668,"duration":5.89},{"text":"Now, I have -- there are several -- there are two things about this first point that I'd like to repeat and reiterate.","start":1238.668,"stop":1251.741,"duration":13.07},{"text":"One is, I think the government should come forward and clearly state what it is, what its position with regard to issue discount prior to 1953 since we are here dealing with the year 1952.","start":1251.741,"stop":1265.585,"duration":13.84},{"text":"And further to explain why, the government did not approach Congress prior to 1954 to amend the statue.","start":1265.585,"stop":1274.897,"duration":9.31},{"text":"Is the government not now in the position where it is coming to this Court and presenting to the Court arguments and reasons that should have been more properly presented to the Congress and which were not presented to the Congress until 1954.","start":1274.897,"stop":1296.062,"duration":21.16},{"text":"The second point that's involved in this case is a matter of fundamental importance and the administration of the tax laws.","start":1296.062,"stop":1309.266,"duration":13.2},{"text":"It involves the question of the extent to which taxpayers are privileged to rely on public pronouncements of the Internal Revenue Service and are privileged to believe that if those pronouncements are changed or if the position set forth therein is changed, they will be changed on the basis that does not discriminate as between taxpayers or as among the taxpayers.","start":1309.266,"stop":1340.884,"duration":31.62},{"text":"The partnership here purchased the securities at a time when it fully believed, because of the preexisting government practice that had been announced in more than one place and particularly announced in the acquiescence in the Fulton's case, that issue of discount when realized would bring about capital gain.","start":1340.884,"stop":1366.854,"duration":25.97},{"text":"The government withdrew the Caulkins acquiescence in 1955.","start":1366.854,"stop":1376.088,"duration":9.23},{"text":"At the time when the Caulkins acquiescence was withdrawn, the government stated that it could not and there was no basis to distinguish the discount element present in any security from the discount element present in any other security.","start":1376.088,"stop":1396.365,"duration":20.28},{"text":"In addition, although the Caulkins acquiescence which was a -- well, let me say this about acquiescence, that all of the things that the treasury may say “the most significant on this side of the table is the acquiescence.”","start":1396.365,"stop":1411.074,"duration":14.71},{"text":"This is what the practitioner and the businessman go high.","start":1411.074,"stop":1417.112,"duration":6.04},{"text":"When the Caulkins acquiescence was withdrawn, the government withdrew it not only retroactively without warning, but withdrew it on a basis that discriminated.","start":1417.112,"stop":1429.421,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You distinguish that – you don't ask us to overrule Automobile Michigan [Inaudible]","start":1429.421,"stop":1432.832,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bernard E. Brandes","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":1432.832,"stop":1433.764,"duration":0.93},{"text":"I ask you to follow Automobile Club of Michigan.","start":1433.764,"stop":1437.942,"duration":4.18},{"text":"In that case if you will remember sir, the Automobile Clubs' exempt status was revoked in 1945 and carried back to 1943.","start":1437.942,"stop":1452.007,"duration":14.07},{"text":"The Automobile Club said that the Commissioner should not be permitted retroactively to change his position.","start":1452.007,"stop":1459.54,"duration":7.53},{"text":"This Court held that the Commissioner is privileged to change his position to correct the mistake of law, but whether he has acted properly always depends on the circumstances of the case.","start":1459.54,"stop":1472.161,"duration":12.62},{"text":"And in the discussion of the circumstances of the case, if my memory serves me correctly, there are two aspects that are emphasized.","start":1472.161,"stop":1480.698,"duration":8.54},{"text":"One is that the carry back to 1943 gave the Automobile Club no cause for complaint, because in 1943 it had already been placed on notice by a publicly issued general counsel's memorandum that clubs such as it would no longer be exempt from tax.","start":1480.698,"stop":1500.554,"duration":19.86},{"text":"And most importantly, when the Internal Revenue Service changed its position, it was uniformly applied clear across the boards to every taxpayer similarly situated.","start":1500.554,"stop":1513.21,"duration":12.66},{"text":"In this case, we have a retroactive application without warning and we have a discriminatory application, because the withdrawal of the Caulkins acquiescence is not applied as against particular taxpayers who purchased a particular kind of security.","start":1513.21,"stop":1533.29,"duration":20.08},{"text":"Even though at the same time, the Internal Revenue Service admitted that there was no basis on which to distinguish one discount security from any other discount security.","start":1533.29,"stop":1543.972,"duration":10.68},{"text":"If I may sir, I should like to save the remaining time.","start":1543.972,"stop":1546.849,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may -- you may Mr. Brandes.","start":1546.849,"stop":1554.286,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Mr. Goodman.","start":1554.286,"stop":1555.566,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1555.566,"stop":1558.876,"duration":3.31},{"text":"Despite the shortage of time available today, I'd like to begin by restating very briefly the facts of this case.","start":1558.876,"stop":1565.706,"duration":6.83},{"text":"The partnership of which the petitioners were members, in 1952 purchased $43 million worth of short-term promissory notes, either directly from the obligor corporations or through brokers -- through dealers and agents.","start":1565.706,"stop":1583.686,"duration":17.98},{"text":"These notes bore no stated rate of interest, but in each case, they were issued at discounts ranging from two and three-eights to three and three-quarters percent.","start":1583.686,"stop":1593.846,"duration":10.16},{"text":"By the end of the tax year, the partnership had sold 20 of these 33 notes for an aggregate gain of $500,000, virtually all of it should be result of discounts at which the notes were originally issued.","start":1593.846,"stop":1607.611,"duration":13.77},{"text":"The other 13 notes remained on hand unmatured.","start":1607.611,"stop":1611.866,"duration":4.25},{"text":"The Commissioner determined that the excess of the face amount of the notes over the amount money for which they were purchased represented interest, accruing over the life of each note, both those that were sold and those that were not sold.","start":1611.866,"stop":1628.547,"duration":16.68},{"text":"And since the partnership was on the accrual basis, the interest accruing on each of the notes was required to be included within the partnership's taxable income for the year and therefore, in the taxpayers distributed shares.","start":1628.547,"stop":1643.345,"duration":14.8},{"text":"The taxpayers concede that this treatment would have been entirely appropriate if the notes that had provided for interest in so many words.","start":1643.345,"stop":1651.178,"duration":7.83},{"text":"But they say, that because the interest element -- because the compensation they received for the use of their money was not specifically labeled as such, but was simply added to the amount which the borrower agreed to pay on the maturity of the notes, that they are not required to accrue it and that they are entitled to treat it as capital gain upon the sale of the notes.","start":1651.178,"stop":1675.588,"duration":24.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Everybody agreed that if -- that the state [Inaudible] or that it would be --","start":1675.588,"stop":1680.791,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":1680.791,"stop":1681.873,"duration":1.08},{"text":"And that is true despite the --","start":1681.873,"stop":1682.966,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Of all [Inaudible]","start":1682.966,"stop":1686.265,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the cases holding it to be true dates from about 1954.","start":1686.265,"stop":1690.657,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1690.657,"stop":1690.883,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Before that time, I think that there was a considerable degree of confusion on this subject. There is no case one way or the other specifically indicating the view prior to 1954.","start":1690.883,"stop":1702.324,"duration":11.44},{"text":"We think this --","start":1702.324,"stop":1702.764,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the acquiescence that you talked about here cover those very interests?","start":1702.764,"stop":1712.881,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course we don't know what the Commissioner's acquiescence covered except a particular case that was before the Court.","start":1712.881,"stop":1719.125,"duration":6.24},{"text":"That was a non-interest bearing security which was issued at a discount for all practical purposes.","start":1719.125,"stop":1726.88,"duration":7.76},{"text":"Our contention on that subject is that the case in which the Commissioner acquiesced doesn't even apply to this case for a somewhat different reason that Mr. Justice White, you talked -- you get into those --","start":1726.88,"stop":1737.632,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the retirement not a sale.","start":1737.632,"stop":1739.245,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Essentially that's right.","start":1739.245,"stop":1740.507,"duration":1.26},{"text":"Yes Mr. Justice Stewart.","start":1740.507,"stop":1742.076,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And under that 178 –","start":1742.076,"stop":1744.221,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1744.221,"stop":1744.842,"duration":0.62},{"text":"That's our position on the Caulkins case.","start":1744.842,"stop":1747.915,"duration":3.07},{"text":"We think the petitioners that --","start":1747.915,"stop":1748.983,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's at the Caulkin?","start":1748.983,"stop":1750.269,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Frank I. Goodman","textObjs":[{"text":"Caulkins, that's the name of it.","start":1750.269,"stop":1754.039,"duration":3.77},{"text":"We think that the petitioner's contention is wholly formalistic and that it becomes all the more extraordinary when one further fact is noted which was not adverted to by Mr. Brandes.","start":1754.039,"stop":1765.292,"duration":11.25},{"text":"The record shows that as each of these notes was purchased, it was immediately pledged as security for a bank loan in an amount exactly equal to the face amount of the note.","start":1765.292,"stop":1777.374,"duration":12.08},{"text":"Now, that indicates I think fairly clearly that the partnership obtained the $43 million with which to purchase these notes by borrowing it from a bank specifically for the purpose.","start":1777.374,"stop":1790.609,"duration":13.23},{"text":"In 1952, it paid interest on the money which it borrowed in the amount of $625,000 and claimed that amount as an ordinary deduction on its income tax return.","start":1790.609,"stop":1802.908,"duration":12.3},{"text":"At the same time, the profit which it realized on the notes which it sold amounted to only $495,000.","start":1802.908,"stop":1810.977,"duration":8.07},{"text":"So the tax consequences aside the net effect of the borrowing and lending transactions was an economic loss of $130,000.","start":1810.977,"stop":1820.734,"duration":9.76},{"text":"Now, the explanation for this seeming folly lies of course in the tax consequences.","start":1820.734,"stop":1826.336,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Assuming that the partners were in the 60% bracket which seems a reasonable assumption, the net effect of their obtaining ordinary interest -- ordinary deduction on the interest which they pay while obtaining capital gain on the interest which they received is to reduce their overall tax bill by $250,000, thus not only completely wiping out the economic loss which they incurred before taxes, but giving them a fairly handsome after-tax profit to boot.","start":1826.336,"stop":1861.87,"duration":35.53},{"text":"And indeed so long as the taxpayers are in the 40% bracket or higher, they stand to gain on this arrangement.","start":1861.87,"stop":1869.098,"duration":7.23},{"text":"To us, this is merely another illustration of the fact that unless the tax law conforms to the economic realities of a transaction, gimmicks and devices will readily be found to exploit the artificiality and to obtain advantages which the Congress never dreamed of giving.","start":1869.098,"stop":1888.273,"duration":19.17},{"text":"Our position could be illustrated by a simple analogy, a disarming analogy as Mr. Brandes has referred to it without saying in anyway why it isn't completely applicable to this case.","start":1888.273,"stop":1900.382,"duration":12.11},{"text":"If A gives B -- A lends B a $100 in return for B's promise to repay the $100 a year later, plus $6 extra, this obligation can be worded in a number of different ways.","start":1900.382,"stop":1916.604,"duration":16.22},{"text":"The note could say a $100 plus 6% interest.","start":1916.604,"stop":1920.126,"duration":3.52},{"text":"It could say a $100 plus 6%, a $100 plus $6 interest, or $100 plus $6 or as in the present case, the note could simply say a $106.","start":1920.126,"stop":1932.336,"duration":12.21},{"text":"Now, every one of these forms of expression obviously means exactly the same thing and our basic position in this case is that the tax consequences of each of these transactions should be exactly the same whether the interest is specifically labeled as such and whether or not it is stated as a percentage of the amount borrowed or as an amount added to what the borrower agrees to repay on maturity.","start":1932.336,"stop":1958.53,"duration":26.19},{"text":"In each case, the $6 increment represents exactly the same thing economically and that is compensation paid by the borrower to the lender in exchange for the use of the lender's money.","start":1958.53,"stop":1972.927,"duration":14.4},{"text":"In short, interest as this Court has defined it in Deputy versus du Pont.","start":1972.927,"stop":1981.412,"duration":8.49},{"text":"Now, in the case of the note with the stated interest of 6%, everyone agrees that an accrual basis taxpayer has to accrue the $6 increment ratably over the term of the note.","start":1981.412,"stop":1993.049,"duration":11.64},{"text":"We say that precisely the same should be true in the case of the non-interest bearing note promising a $106 at maturity.","start":1993.049,"stop":2003.279,"duration":10.23}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar  30 - 31, 1965","petitioner":"Dixon","respondent":"United States","docket":"486","citation":"381 US 68 (1965)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/381/68","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 3, 1965"}